page.title: 01NATIONAL PARK
page.content: The towns of Fishguard and Goodwick are situated on the edge of The National Park, an area popular with hilidaymakers because of the natural beauty of unspoiled coast line and countryside. There are sandy beaches and coastal footpaths, valleys and low hills inland. There are numerous varieties of wild flowers to be found. Many different kinds of sea_birds may also be seen. The countryside gives shelter to both birds and small creatures such as rabbits, foxes and weasels. Even lizards and grass snakes are to be found. The historical heritage of the area may be traced to the Stone Age and is another attraction of the area.
